#
#  Usage:
#    arrow2csv [options] [<file.arrow>...]
#    cat file.arrow | arrow2csv [options]
#
#  Options:
#    -s, --schema <COLUMNS...>      A space-delimited list of
#                                   column names to include in
#                                   the output.  When absent,
#                                   all columns are printed.
#                                   Useful for filtering wide
#                                   Arrow files to specific
#                                   columns of interest.
#    -f, --file <PATH...>           The Arrow file to read (can
#                                   be specified multiple times
#                                   for batch processing;
#                                   alternative to passing
#                                   files as bare positional
#                                   args)
#        --sep <CHAR>               The column separator
#                                   character (Default: " | ").
#                                   Use " , " for traditional
#                                   CSV output, " \t " for TSV.
#        --hr <CHAR>                The horizontal border
#                                   character (Default: empty
#                                   = no horizontal rules).
#                                   Use "-" or "=" for visible
#                                   row separators.
#    -m, --metadata                 Flag to also print Schema
#                                   metadata (Arrow files can
#                                   carry per-column and per-
#                                   schema metadata as
#                                   key-value strings;
#                                   default: false — metadata
#                                   suppressed)
#        --help                     Print usage guide (rendered
#                                   via command-line-usage from
#                                   the same cliOpts() array)
#
#  Positional:
#    <FILE.arrow>...                Arrow file paths (bare
#                                   positional args; equivalent
#                                   to -f/--file).  May be
#                                   combined with --file or
#                                   used alone.  When NO files
#                                   are given AND stdin is not
#                                   a TTY, reads from stdin
#                                   (allows piping `cat
#                                   file.arrow | arrow2csv`).
#
#  Examples:
#    arrow2csv data.arrow                                       # Print all columns of data.arrow
#    arrow2csv --file data.arrow                                # Same (explicit -f)
#    arrow2csv -f data.arrow                                    # Same (short form)
#    cat data.arrow | arrow2csv                                 # Read from stdin
#    arrow2csv --schema name age data.arrow                     # Only name + age columns
#    arrow2csv -s name age data.arrow                           # Same (short form)
#    arrow2csv --schema name age --sep " , " data.arrow         # CSV-style output
#    arrow2csv --sep " | " --hr "-" data.arrow                  # With horizontal rules
#    arrow2csv -m data.arrow                                    # Include schema metadata
#    arrow2csv -f a.arrow -f b.arrow -f c.arrow                 # Multiple files
#    arrow2csv data.arrow > output.csv                          # Redirect to file
